# ACS / OpenClaw Dreaming Mode Strategy

## Purpose

Dreaming Mode is the scheduled memory and synthesis routine for ACS/OpenClaw agents.

It exists to help agents:

- summarize recent operational events;
- extract relevant decisions;
- identify unresolved tasks;
- detect project drift;
- refresh local memory context;
- prepare concise handoff notes for future runs;
- surface risks, blockers, and governance-relevant events.

Dreaming Mode must not:

- implement code;
- change production systems;
- execute transactions;
- approve governance decisions;
- rewrite canonical project history without validation;
- create uncontrolled long-term memory from noisy context;
- persist secrets, credentials, private keys, wallet data, auth headers, tokens, or sensitive logs.

## Operating Principle

Dreaming Mode creates memory proposals. It does not define canonical truth.

Every output must distinguish:

- observed facts;
- inferred conclusions;
- open questions;
- risks;
- proposed memory candidates;
- items that should be ignored or forgotten.

Agents must handle uncertainty explicitly. If evidence is weak, contradictory, stale, or local-only, the output must mark the confidence as `Low` or `Medium` and avoid promotion language.

## Dreaming Layers

Dreaming runs in four layers.

| Layer | Owner | Purpose | Canonical Authority |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Agent Local Dreaming | Individual agent | Summarize role-specific recent context | No |
| Nucleus Dreaming | Nucleus/domain routine | Summarize domain-level state | No |
| ACS Coordinator Dreaming | ACS coordinator | Consolidate agent and nucleus outputs | No |
| Core Memory Registry Sync | Core review workflow | Review candidates for canonical promotion | Proposal only until approved |

## 1. Agent Local Dreaming

Each agent summarizes only what belongs to its operational role.

Examples:

- Morpheus: strategy, synthesis, governance direction, unresolved planning questions, cross-nucleus decisions.
- Trinity: trading intelligence, capital/risk analysis, trading nucleus continuity, strategy review, backtest planning status.
- Agent Smith: adversarial review, inconsistencies, duplicated assumptions, governance/security concerns, policy drift.
- RedHat: engineering planning, MCP/tooling risks, implementation constraints, automation boundaries.

Agent Local Dreaming should produce short, structured reports. It must not generate broad project truth or update canonical memory directly.

## 2. Nucleus Dreaming

Nucleus Dreaming groups context by Axodus domain rather than by agent.

Supported nuclei include:

- Governance;
- ACS;
- Core;
- Academy;
- Trading;
- Marketplace;
- Business;
- DeFi;
- DEX;
- Lottery;
- Mining;
- BBA Agency;
- AxodusAPP.

The purpose is to answer:

- what changed in this nucleus;
- which decisions became stable;
- which tasks are blocked;
- which assumptions conflict with Core or Governance policy;
- which items should become memory candidates.

Nucleus Dreaming should run only for active nuclei with relevant changes.

## 3. ACS Coordinator Dreaming

The ACS Coordinator is the consolidation layer.

It reviews recent Agent Local Dreaming and Nucleus Dreaming outputs and produces:

- global project digest;
- cross-nucleus dependencies;
- duplicated or conflicting memories;
- drift warnings;
- proposed canonical memory updates;
- recommended next sprints;
- unresolved architecture questions.

The coordinator must not overwrite Core policy, approve memory, or treat repeated claims as true without stable supporting context.

## 4. Core Memory Registry Sync

Core Memory Registry Sync is the review layer for canonical promotion.

The flow is:

```text
Dreaming Output
→ Memory Candidate
→ Review / Classification
→ Approved Canonical Candidate
→ Core Registry Update Proposal
→ Agent Context Refresh
```

Canonical files must not be changed by routine dreaming unless a future approved Core workflow explicitly authorizes it.

## Boundaries

Dreaming Mode may:

- read recent local context available to the agent;
- summarize sprint reports and operational notes;
- classify memory candidates;
- identify drift, duplicates, risks, blockers, and follow-up tasks;
- write structured dreaming output to approved dreaming output paths.

Dreaming Mode must not:

- execute code changes;
- mutate source/config/runtime/auth/bindings;
- change cron schedules;
- call MCP tools or runtime shells;
- access network tools unless separately authorized by policy;
- approve or execute governance/treasury/trading actions;
- write canonical memory directly;
- persist secrets or sensitive raw logs.

## Recommended Output Paths

Use structured output paths:

```text
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/agents/<agent-name>/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/nuclei/<nucleus-name>/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/coordinator/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/memory-candidates/
~/.openclaw/main_workspace/dreaming/outputs/registry-sync/
```

Optional repository-local references may live under:

```text
.instructions/agents/
.instructions/memory/
.instructions/status/
```

## Anti-Drift Rules

- Repeated claims are not automatically true.
- Speculation is not a stable fact.
- Temporary execution details should expire.
- Cross-agent contradictions must be surfaced, not merged silently.
- Canonical promotion requires review under Core policy.
- Security and governance constraints override convenience.
